  "text": "The feature selection analysis has brought to light such valuable information as the predictability of mobility scores from outing patterns, daily routine, and patterns of cooking and eating. In the specific case of TUG scores, there was a significant correlation with global overnight activities including bed-totoilet transitions. This finding suggests that individuals who take longer to complete the TUG (indicative of slowed movement) tend to be more active at night. This is supported by the AD literature that finds both impaired mobility and sleep disturbances to be related to dementia [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] . In [CITATION_3] , TUG showed significant correlations with mobility, outings, sleep and ADL (cook, eat, relax and personal hygiene activities) features.",
